{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CZV6dJuYc8nDVAVGudk7Ue","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Specification: [301] Async Event Queue\n     2→\n     3→## Meta\n     4→\n     5→| Field | Value |\n     6→|-------|-------|\n     7→| Status | Done |\n     8→| Priority | P1 |\n     9→| Track | Core |\n    10→| NR_OF_TRIES | 8 |\n    11→\n    12→---\n    13→\n    14→## Overview\n    15→\n    16→A Postgres-backed async event queue that decouples the critical game settlement path from secondary side-effects: reward delivery, claim payouts, achievement evaluation, notifications, and analytics. The queue is a platform-level primitive — not tied to any single feature — with the referral system (spec 300) as its first consumer.\n    17→\n    18→**Why this exists:** The settlement worker is the hot path. Every millisecond of latency there is felt by players waiting for results. Side-effects like sending SOL, granting rewards, checking achievements, or firing notifications are slower, can fail independently, and must never block or degrade the game loop. A queue also provides natural backpressure — 50 games settling simultaneously don't DDoS the treasury wallet or external services.\n    19→\n    20→## User Stories\n    21→\n    22→- As a platform developer, I want to emit events from the settlement path without adding latency so that players see results instantly\n    23→- As a platform developer, I want failed side-effects to retry automatically so that transient failures (RPC timeouts, treasury wallet congestion) self-heal\n    24→- As an operator, I want visibility into dead events so that I can investigate and manually resolve stuck operations\n    25→- As a platform developer, I want to register new event handlers without modifying the queue infrastructure so that new features plug in cleanly\n    26→\n    27→---\n    28→\n    29→## Capability Alignment\n    30→\n    31→- **`docs/SCOPE.md` references**: Section 7 \"Non-Functional Baseline\" → Reliability, Observability\n    32→- **Current baseline fit**: Not Implemented\n    33→- **Planning bucket**: Core (infrastructure primitive)\n    34→\n    35→## Required Context Files\n    36→\n    37→- Backend settlement worker (current hot path)\n    38→- Backend DB client and migration system (see `docs/solutions/` or memory for patterns)\n    39→- `docs/FOUNDATIONS.md` — architecture patterns\n    40→\n    41→## Contract Files\n    42→\n    43→- No existing mocks — new infrastructure\n    44→- Producer API and worker interface defined in FR-2 and FR-3 below\n    45→\n    46→---\n    47→\n    48→## Functional Requirements\n    49→\n    50→### FR-1: Event Table Schema\n    51→\n    52→A single `event_queue` table in the existing Postgres database. No external dependencies — no Redis, no RabbitMQ, no SQS.\n    53→\n    54→```sql\n    55→CREATE TABLE event_queue (\n    56→  id              BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n    57→  event_type      TEXT NOT NULL,\n    58→  payload         JSONB NOT NULL,\n    59→  status          TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'pending',\n    60→  attempts        INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,\n    61→  max_attempts    INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 3,\n    62→  scheduled_at    TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),\n    63→  started_at      TIMESTAMPTZ,\n    64→  completed_at    TIMESTAMPTZ,\n    65→  error           TEXT,\n    66→  created_at      TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()\n    67→);\n    68→\n    69→-- Partial index for worker polling — only scans pending events\n    70→CREATE INDEX idx_event_queue_poll\n    71→  ON event_queue (scheduled_at)\n    72→  WHERE status = 'pending';\n    73→\n    74→-- Index for observability queries (dead events, recent failures)\n    75→CREATE INDEX idx_event_queue_status ON event_queue (status, created_at);\n    76→```\n    77→\n    78→**Status lifecycle:**\n    79→```\n    80→pending → processing → completed\n    81→                    → failed → pending (retry with backoff)\n    82→                             → dead (max_attempts exceeded)\n    83→```\n    84→\n    85→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n    86→- [x] `event_queue` table created via migration <!-- satisfied: migrations/010_event_queue.sql:7-22 -->\n    87→- [x] Partial index on `(scheduled_at) WHERE status = 'pending'` exists <!-- satisfied: migrations/010_event_queue.sql:25-27 idx_event_queue_poll -->\n    88→- [x] Status index for observability queries exists <!-- satisfied: migrations/010_event_queue.sql:30-31 idx_event_queue_status on (status, created_at) -->\n    89→- [x] Status values constrained to: `pending`, `processing`, `completed`, `failed`, `dead` <!-- satisfied: migrations/010_event_queue.sql:20-21 chk_event_queue_status CHECK constraint -->\n    90→\n    91→### FR-2: Event Producer API\n    92→\n    93→A minimal function that inserts an event into the queue. Designed to be called **within an existing DB transaction** so the event is committed atomically with the triggering operation.\n    94→\n    95→```typescript\n    96→// Signature\n    97→async function emitEvent(\n    98→  tx: DatabaseTransaction,   // existing transaction handle\n    99→  eventType: string,\n   100→  payload: Record<string, unknown>,\n   101→  options?: {\n   102→    maxAttempts?: number;     // default: 3\n   103→    scheduledAt?: Date;       // default: now (for delayed events)\n   104→  }\n   105→): Promise<{ eventId: bigint }>;\n   106→```\n   107→\n   108→**Usage example (in settlement worker):**\n   109→```typescript\n   110→await db.transaction(async (tx) => {\n   111→  // 1. Existing: write settlement outcome\n   112→  await settleGame(tx, roundId, outcome);\n   113→\n   114→  // 2. Existing: insert referral earnings (fast, inline)\n   115→  await insertReferralEarning(tx, referrerWallet, ...);\n   116→\n   117→  // 3. New: emit event for async processing (reward delivery, notifications)\n   118→  await emitEvent(tx, 'referral.game_settled', {\n   119→    referrerWallet, refereeWallet, roundId, gameType, wagerLamports, earnedLamports\n   120→  });\n   121→});\n   122→// All three committed atomically — or none.\n   123→```\n   124→\n   125→**Key property:** If the settlement transaction rolls back, the event is never created. No orphan events. No missed events.\n   126→\n   127→**Acceptance Criteria:**\n   128→- [x] `emitEvent()` function inserts into `event_queue` within the provided transaction <!-- satisfied: src/queue/emit-event.ts:18-34 -->\n   129→- [x] Event is committed atomically with the triggering operation <!-- satisfied: queue.test.ts:76-98 rollback test proves non-persistence -->\n   130→- [x] Default `max_attempts` is 3, overridable per event <!-- satisfied: emit-event.ts:24 default=3, queue.test.ts:100-119 custom maxAttempts=5 -->\n   131→- [x] `scheduled_at` defaults to `now()`, supports future scheduling for delayed events <!-- satisfied: emit-event.ts:25 default new Date(), queue.test.ts:100-119 future date -->\n   132→- [x] Returns the created event's ID <!-- satisfied: emit-event.ts:33 returns { eventId: BigInt(...) }, queue.test.ts:57-58 -->\n   133→\n   134→### FR-3: Event Worker\n   135→\n   136→A single polling loop that runs inside the existing backend process. No separate service, no separate deploy.\n   137→\n   138→**Polling loop:**\n   139→1. Every 1-2 seconds, query for ready events:\n   140→   ```sql\n   141→   UPDATE event_queue\n   142→   SET status = 'processing', started_at = now()\n   143→   WHERE id IN (\n   144→     SELECT id FROM event_queue\n   145→     WHERE status = 'pending' AND scheduled_at <= now()\n   146→     ORDER BY scheduled_at\n   147→     LIMIT 10\n   148→     FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED\n   149→   )\n   150→   RETURNING *;"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01EsZ149HxsCGBH7ihZWCDXq","session_id":"22eabd0a-3a3b-489d-bc57-d8e8d222d116","uuid":"64c2a91a-b413-4694-a192-fa4b65b3c203","timestamp":"2026-03-24T21:25:09.898Z"}
